{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3c4cf1b3-5f99-4fb3-88f7-ba9612e324f5","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options available via `--auth`:\n\n| Option | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single-tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```bash\n# Basic API with no auth\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n\n# With Azure AD single-org auth\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth SingleOrg --domain yourdomain.onmicrosoft.com\n\n# With Azure AD B2C\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth IndividualB2C\n```\n\nRun `dotnet new webapi --help` for the full list of options. For JWT bearer auth without Azure AD, start with `None` and add `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` manually.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5107778a-c3e0-4453-b107-4ba5633afa96","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":327,"requestId":"A84A:2BC4D4:42E5CA3:495114F:69F155F1"},"id":"eea339e7-870c-4296-9840-15d4a609cf6e","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:51:05.424Z","parentId":"fa7603e5-4586-4475-a0c8-c064f8de8949"}
